<DOC><DOCNO> AP890422-0111 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-22-89 1752EST</FILEID><FIRST>r i AM-Portugal-Police     04-22 0241</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Portugal-Police,0248</SECOND><HEAD>Prime Minister Condemns Extremists in Police</HEAD><DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Prime Minister Anibal Cavaco Silva onSaturday blamed extreme leftists for prompting demands by policeofficers to form a union, news reports said. The demands provokedviolent clashes within the police force.   Six policemen were arrested in the clashes Friday between riotpolice and fellow officers demanding union rights. They werereleased Saturday pending trial. About 100 uniformed officersgreeted the release with victory signs and calls for furtherprotest.   Riot police used water cannons, dogs and batons Friday againstprotesting officers outside the Internal Affairs Ministry.   As the riot escalated, civilians joined demonstrators in hurlingstones at the riot squad. Seventeen people were reported injured.   ``Extremist forces, communist forces and some socialists werebehind the movements in the Public Security Police,'' Silva wasquoted by the national Lusa news agency as saying.   Cavaco Silva's center-right Social Democratic government has notgranted union rights to uniformed police units, saying theirmilitarized status makes trade unions unconstitutional.   Portugal's two major trade union federations, theCommunist-inspired General Confederation of Portuguese Workers andthe Socialist-led General Workers Union, called for a demonstrationMonday to protest the actions of the riot police.   General Workers Union General Secretary Jose Torres Couto, alsoa Socialist deputy in the National Assembly, said he would ask fora parliamentary inquiry into Friday's riot and demanded theresignation of Internal Affairs Minister Jose Antonio da SilveiraGodinho.</TEXT></DOC>